DOMAIN_SEPARATOR().details: This is not cached because chainid can change on chain forks.

acceptMintership(address).details: Can only be called by the proposed minter.

approve(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-approve}. NOTE: If `amount` is the maximum `uint256`, the allowance is not updated on `transferFrom`. This is semantically equivalent to an infinite approval. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

burn(address,uint256).details: Can only be called by the minter address.

params.account: The address that will have its tokens burnt.
params.amount: The amount of tokens to burn.

constructor.details: Makes the implementation act as if it has been setup already to disallow calls to init() (even though that would not achieve anything really).

decreaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically decreases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address. - `spender` must have allowance for the caller of at least `subtractedValue`.

returns._0: True if the account has the role, false otherwise

increaseAllowance(address,uint256).details: Atomically increases the allowance granted to `spender` by the caller. This is an alternative to {approve} that can be used as a mitigation for problems described in {IERC20-approve}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

params.minter: The address of the token minter.

returns._0: address The interchain token service contract

interchainTransfer(string,bytes,uint256,.details: We chose to either pass `metadata` as raw data on a remote contract call, or if no data is passed, just do a transfer. A different implementation could use metadata to specify a function to invoke, or for other purposes as well.

params.amount: The amount of token to be transferred.
params.metadata: Either empty, just to facilitate an interchain transfer, or the data to be passed for an interchain contract call with transfer as per semantics defined by the token service.
params.recipient: The bytes representation of the address of the recipient.

interchainTransferFrom(address,string,by.details: We chose to either pass `metadata` as raw data on a remote contract call, or, if no data is passed, just do a transfer. A different implementation could use metadata to specify a function to invoke, or for other purposes as well.

params.amount: The amount of token to be transferred.
params.destinationChain: The string representation of the destination chain.
params.metadata: Either empty, just to facilitate an interchain transfer, or the data to be passed to an interchain contract call and transfer.
params.recipient: The bytes representation of the address of the recipient.
params.sender: The sender of the tokens. They need to have approved `msg.sender` before this is called.

returns._0: bool Boolean value representing whether or not the address is a minter.

mint(address,uint256).details: Can only be called by the minter address.

params.account: The address that will receive the minted tokens.
params.amount: The amount of tokens to mint.

permit(address,address,uint256,uint256,u.details: The permit function is used to allow a holder to designate a spender to spend tokens on their behalf via a signed message.

params.deadline: The time at which the permission to spend expires
params.issuer: The address of the token holder
params.r: Half of the ECDSA signature pair
params.s: Half of the ECDSA signature pair
params.spender: The address of the designated spender
params.v: The recovery id of the signature
params.value: The number of tokens to be spent

proposeMintership(address).details: Can only be called by the current minter.

params.minter_: The address of the new minter.

transfer(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transfer}. Requirements: - `recipient` cannot be the zero address. - the caller must have a balance of at least `amount`.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transferFrom}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. This is not required by the EIP. See the note at the beginning of {ERC20}. Requirements: - `sender` and `recipient` cannot be the zero address. - `sender` must have a balance of at least `amount`. - the caller must have allowance for ``sender``'s tokens of at least `amount`.

transferMintership(address).details: Can only be called by the current minter.

params.minter_: The address of the new minter.
